[[File:françois-joseph-fournier-sépulture.jpg| The tomb of Fournier in Porquerolles|thumb]]
'''François Joseph Fournier''' (December 6, 1857 - January 13, 1935) was a [[Autodidacticism|self-taught]] [[Belgians|Belgian]] [[adventurer]] and [[entrepreneur]]  who explored [[Mexico]] and the island of [[Porquerolles]]. He was born into a family of modest means, in [[Clabecq]], [[Belgium]] and died on Porquerolles.

Fournier purchased the entire island of Porquerolles in 1912, apparently as a wedding present for his wife. He planted 200 [[hectare]]s (about 500 [[acre]]s) of vineyards which produced a wine that was among the first to be [[French_wine#Quality_levels_and_appellation_system|classed]] [[French_wine#Provence|des Côtes de Provence]].

