'''Shlomo Zabludowicz''' ({{lang-he|שלמה זבלודוביץ'}}; 1914&ndash;1994) was a Polish-born Israeli businessman. He gained wealth through the armament trade between the Finnish weapons manufacturer [[Tampella]] and Israel.<ref name="HS">{{cite news |last=Miettinen |first=Anssi |date=September 2011 |title=Isänsä poika |url= |newspaper=[[Helsingin Sanomat]] Kuukausiliite |pages=25–33 }}</ref>
Zabludowicz was born in a Jewish family in [[Łódź]], Poland. His father was a rabbi. Zabludowicz and his family was interned at the [[Auschwitz concentration camp]], where only he and his wife Pola survived. After the war, he immigrated to Finland via Sweden.<ref name="HS" /> In Finland, he had two children, business magnate [[Poju Zabludowicz]] and ophthalmologist [[Rebecka Belldegrun]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Coren |first=Ora |date=12 October 2004 |title=Soltam heirs near end of feud over father's $200-300m fortune |url=http://www.haaretz.com/print-edition/business/soltam-heirs-near-end-of-feud-over-father-s-200-300m-fortune-1.137164 |newspaper=[[Haaretz]]}}</ref> In 1975, he immigrated to Israel.<ref name="HS" />
Zabludowicz founded the investment firm [[Tamares]] that is currently owned by his son Poju. Zabludowicz was a prominent figure in creating the joint enterprise between Tampella and [[Solel Boneh]], [[Soltam Systems]]. In the 1980s, he distanced himself from the arms industry and began moving his investments to property.<ref name="HS" />
